&gt;&gt; Thank you very much Cheryl
and welcome everybody.

00:00:50.430 --> 00:00:56.440
Hopefully, we'll get some good
discussion during today's session

00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:58.850 position:61%
and I'll just go ahead and get started.

00:00:58.850 --> 00:01:04.410 position:67%
Today I am going to talk with you about
Chronicling in America, an ongoing resource

00:01:04.410 --> 00:01:09.260 position:67%
from the National Digital Newspaper Program
which is collaboration between the Library

00:01:09.260 --> 00:01:13.670 position:59%
of Congress, the National Endowment
of the Humanities and state partners .

00:01:13.670 --> 00:01:17.590
We frequently get the question
-- why use newspapers?

00:01:17.590 --> 00:01:20.260
Are newspapers primary sources?

00:01:20.260 --> 00:01:22.690
And yes, they are.

00:01:22.690 --> 00:01:24.440 position:56%
That's the answer we generally give.

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:30.690 position:69%
A more in-depth explanation would be primary
sources are the raw materials of history --

00:01:30.690 --> 00:01:35.080 position:61%
original documents and objects which
were created at the time of your study.

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:39.040 position:70%
They are different from secondary sources --
accounts or interpretations of events created

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:41.840 position:64%
by someone without first-hand experience.

00:01:41.840 --> 00:01:43.600
So what is chronically America?

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:47.510 position:61%
Chronicling America is digitized copies

00:01:47.510 --> 00:01:50.420
of historic newspapers from
across the United States.

00:01:50.420 --> 00:01:55.120 position:59%
We recently expanded the date coverage
to include issues of newspapers

00:01:55.120 --> 00:01:59.950
from the early cross of the US
capitals -- so going back to 1789.

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:03.930
Currently, 43 state partners,
DC and Puerto Rico, participate

00:02:03.930 --> 00:02:06.320
and we have over 11 million pages.

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:09.390
The goal of the program has
been to enhance access

00:02:09.390 --> 00:02:14.020 position:64%
to historic American newspapers
hopefully from every state and territory.

00:02:14.020 --> 00:02:21.880 position:72%
Once we progress long enough to apply emerging
technologies to the products of the US.

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:24.690
newspaper program.

00:02:24.690 --> 00:02:26.670
Including Chronicling America.

00:02:26.670 --> 00:02:31.530 position:72%
To develop best practices for the digitization
of historic newspapers and to provide free

00:02:31.530 --> 00:02:34.660 position:72%
and open content that's available to everyone.

00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:40.700
Here's a map of this current
participating state partners.

00:02:40.700 --> 00:02:48.020 position:59%
We have over 300,000 pages in French,
Italian, German, Spanish, and Finnish.

00:02:48.020 --> 00:02:53.370
And actually as of this year
[inaudible] will have the option

00:02:53.370 --> 00:03:01.460 position:61%
to select any public domain content
published -- even published after 1922.

00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:06.780
I believe the date range
for that goes up to 1963.

00:03:06.780 --> 00:03:13.080 position:63%
So in the coming years, we will actually
have additional content passed 1922.

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:16.540 position:63%
There's over 2,000 titles at the moment.

00:03:16.540 --> 00:03:21.700 position:56%
The titles that were actually
selected for inclusion were selected

00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:24.960
by the state partners themselves.

00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:29.870 position:75%
Generally, they're not available elsewhere
online and were identified by the state partners

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:33.710 position:59%
at risk for loss without preservation.

00:03:33.710 --> 00:03:39.590 position:67%
Something you might note is that there are
only select dates available for each title.

00:03:39.590 --> 00:03:44.140 position:56%
Sometimes this can be because they
were only a certain number of issues

00:03:44.140 --> 00:03:46.730 position:75%
that were available at the time of digitization.

00:03:46.730 --> 00:03:51.210
Sometimes those are the only
issues that exists anywhere.

00:03:51.210 --> 00:03:55.790 position:59%
Each title is researched and selected
by the state partners, as I mentioned,

00:03:55.790 --> 00:04:01.240 position:64%
and if the state partner continues the
program and identifies additional issues,

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:08.750
I believe they do try to add new
issues as they are discovered.

00:04:08.750 --> 00:04:12.400
All right, so what you might
notice is the search bar that's

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:15.540 position:61%
on the homepage of Chronicling America.

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:17.750 position:58%
This is the, sort of, default search.

00:04:17.750 --> 00:04:19.110
We call it the Simple search.

00:04:19.110 --> 00:04:27.560 position:56%
You can select a state, a date range
by year, and enter keywords in.

00:04:27.560 --> 00:04:32.320 position:56%
The searching is a proximity search,
so it will search the words you type

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:34.920 position:56%
in within five words of one another.

00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:42.210 position:64%
And generally, we find that this is
pretty useful for most keyword searching.

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:46.340 position:61%
Once you've entered a keyword search,
what you'll see is something like this.

00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:48.330 position:64%
I did a search for presidential election.

00:04:48.330 --> 00:04:55.220
The results allow you to visually
scan the pages and take note

00:04:55.220 --> 00:04:58.620 position:73%
of how many times the terms appear on the page.

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:06.560 position:66%
So the red box that you see there, you can
kind of observe whether the terms are part

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:14.840 position:75%
of the head line -- whether there a caption from
an image -- whether there are any images or not.

00:05:14.840 --> 00:05:16.310
Excuse me.

00:05:16.310 --> 00:05:23.030 position:73%
The default sort is relevant but you can change
that to date, title, or state, I believe.

00:05:23.030 --> 00:05:26.990 position:72%
Something that you might find useful, as well,

00:05:26.990 --> 00:05:33.140
is seeing how many times the
terms appear on the page.

00:05:33.140 --> 00:05:39.420
Pages that have fewer words,
total per page, will rank higher.

00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:44.410
So, it can be as you see here,
where ads will come up first.

00:05:44.410 --> 00:05:50.660
But sometimes the ads are
actually very interesting.

00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:56.620 position:69%
For a variety of reasons they include images
and, that kind of, gives you a feeling

00:05:56.620 --> 00:06:01.160
of what popular reaction was like.

00:06:02.650 --> 00:06:12.340 position:73%
What you might notice, here, is that the --
you can see that there are some ways of sorting

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:16.370
and limiting as I mentioned, but
also that the search resulted

00:06:16.370 --> 00:06:21.730
in 130,245 results containing
presidential elections.

00:06:21.730 --> 00:06:23.390
Which is quite a few.

00:06:23.390 --> 00:06:27.190 position:66%
You can limit it to show only front pages.

00:06:27.190 --> 00:06:33.180 position:56%
Often front pages -- front page
results include headlines and images

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:35.950 position:70%
which you might find useful in the classroom.

00:06:35.950 --> 00:06:42.760 position:66%
Another way to limit, might be to select a
particular state or particular date range.

00:06:42.760 --> 00:06:49.060 position:63%
But you can also use the advanced search
feature to narrow your results further.

00:06:51.570 --> 00:06:53.950 position:58%
So, this is the advanced search page.

00:06:53.950 --> 00:07:02.310 position:63%
And just in case you have not discovered
this yet, I -- all of the pages --

00:07:02.310 --> 00:07:08.180
the images should be hyperlinked,
so you can go back to the page

00:07:08.180 --> 00:07:11.860 position:61%
or go into the page on your own, later.

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:15.900 position:73%
So, as I mentioned the -- excuse me [coughs] --

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:19.790
the Simple search defaults to
what I call the proximity search

00:07:19.790 --> 00:07:22.040 position:61%
which you see in the lower left corner.

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:31.230 position:59%
The Advanced search allows you to do
a couple different types of searching.

00:07:31.230 --> 00:07:34.270
The Any, All and the Phrase search.

00:07:34.270 --> 00:07:41.780
You can also enter a date -- a more
specific date range -- then years.

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:47.380 position:61%
It allows you to select from a calendar
view, which can be useful if you know

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:52.710 position:70%
that you're looking for reporting on a
particular -- particular event say, you know,

00:07:52.710 --> 00:07:58.580 position:67%
the election of 1860 and reporting on that.

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:03.200
So, from November in 1860 you can
search for presidential election

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:06.880
and get a more narrow result list.

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:10.040
One thing to bear in mind when
using the date range though,

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:14.390 position:61%
is that instantaneous news may not have
been the norm during the time period

00:08:14.390 --> 00:08:16.100
that you're researching.

00:08:16.100 --> 00:08:25.570
Even though technological advances
such as telegraph and cable wire,

00:08:25.570 --> 00:08:30.140 position:64%
cable news service existed,
instantaneous reporting was not the norm.

00:08:30.140 --> 00:08:36.300 position:72%
And so, it could take days for events be re --
that happened on the east coast to be reported

00:08:36.300 --> 00:08:39.150
on the west coast and vice versa.

00:08:39.150 --> 00:08:45.000
Especially the earlier you get.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:50.920
So to go back to the search results
-- sorry that's a little blurry --

00:08:50.920 --> 00:08:59.160 position:69%
what you'll see is individual pages with the
keywords you selected highlighted in red.

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:04.670 position:69%
This we call Hit Highlighting and it allows,
as I mentioned, you to visually browse.

00:09:04.670 --> 00:09:11.210
Something that I wanted to mention
was that sometimes you might find

00:09:11.210 --> 00:09:13.150 position:59%
that the expected language or keywords

00:09:13.150 --> 00:09:19.800
that you're using are not actually
use during the time period.

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:25.440 position:56%
Similarly, headlines were not used
in the same way that they are today.

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:34.920 position:64%
One example, that I will show in a little
bit is actually the election of 1860.

00:09:34.920 --> 00:09:41.700
Headlines did not read like
they did in even 1916.

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:46.900
It just said Election across
one tiny part of the page.

00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:50.570
So, just bear that in mind
when you're searching.

00:09:50.570 --> 00:09:54.520 position:58%
It may depend on the time period,
what kind of results you are getting.

00:09:54.520 --> 00:10:01.160 position:70%
Sometimes, you can also get additional useful
keywords by reading some of the articles

00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:02.610 position:67%
that you might not have thought of as well.

00:10:02.610 --> 00:10:13.550 position:75%
&gt;&gt; So clicking on one of the results pages will
show you this -- each page has a permanent link.

00:10:13.550 --> 00:10:17.040 position:66%
It will allow you to view the entire page.

00:10:17.040 --> 00:10:23.100 position:75%
Include the highlighted keywords and it includes
the citation information on the top and bottom

00:10:23.100 --> 00:10:26.430
